Cyclistic_Bike_Share_Case_Study

James Souder

2023-04-27

Business Task

  • What is the problem you are trying to solve? To understand how annual riders and casual cyclists differ.

  • How can your insights drive business decisions? They can be used to develop a marketing strategy aimed at converting casual riders.

Statement of the business task: Understand the differences in annual riders and casual riders to develop a marketing strategy to convert casual to annual riders.

Prepare

# Read and merge multiple csv files

  # bind_rows

# Only using most recent month of data for computational efficiency
df <- read_csv("~/Desktop/data_analyst_course/cyclistic_bike_case_study/data/202303-divvy-tripdata.csv")
names(df)

# check for duplicate ride IDs
n_occur <- data.frame(table(df$ride_id))
n_occur[n_occur$Freq > 1,]

#Sort the data
df <- df %>% arrange(started_at)

Description of data

  • The data is hosted at https://divvy-tripdata.s3.amazonaws.com/index.html. It is updated in monthly intervals and is collected directly from Cyclistic.

  • Data integrity: The accuracy, completeness, consistency, and trustworthiness of data throughout its life cycle. The data meets all of the criteria for data integrity.

  • The data is organized into 13 columns containing information such as bike station, start and finish datetime, and membership status.

Process

A documentation of cleaning and manipulation of data

The following columns were created in google sheets:

  • ride_length
  • day_of_week

Cleaning data set and feature engineering:

#drop the following cols
df <- df %>% select(-c(ride_id, start_station_id, end_station_id,ended_at))

# Create year, month, day columns
df$Date <- as.Date(df$started_at)
df <- separate(df,Date, c("year","month","day"), sep='-')

# lat degree = 69 miles, long degree = 54.6 miles
df <- df %>% mutate(manhattan_distance_miles = abs(start_lat - end_lat)*69 + abs(start_lng - end_lng)*54.6)

Act

Top Three Recommendations

  1. Casuals prefer electric bikes. I recommend discount electric bike rentals for members.

  2. Membership rides drop off on the weekends, while casual rides stay about the same. Target ads on weekends to convert casual riders.

  3. Median ride length and distance spikes for casuals on weekends. Weekend deals for member riders.
